General accidental release prevention and chemical-specific prevention steps:



MPM Silicones has implemented a comprehensive program to prevent accidental releases of hazardous chemicals known as Process Safety Management (PSM).  The facility is also subject to the New York State Chemical Bulk Storage (CBS) regulation that focuses on preventing spills and releases from hazardous material storage tanks.  Both programs are an integral part of the safety-related operations at MPM Silicones.  PSM helps to ensure that proper safety information is in place, operating procedures are followed, chemical hazards are identified, employees and contractors are properly trained, and critical equipment is properly inspected and maintained.  Some of the many specific features in place at MPM Silicones to minimize the potential for a chemical accident include:

* Computerized process control systems on chlorosilane and methyl chloride chemical reaction and purification systems to ensure that any deviations from the intended operating conditions (e.g. pressure, temperature, vessel level, flow rate) are immediately identified and corrected;

* Instrumentation and safety procedures that reduce the potential for human error that could lead to a storage tank overfill;

* Secondary containment dikes around storage tanks and loading stations to contain a spill;

* Hydrogen chloride and methyl chloride gas sensors to detect and warn of a release;

* Extensive safety information about the processes reviewed with employees and contractors;

* Written operating procedures that include emergency response actions and safety shut down instructions;

* Comprehensive employee and contractor training programs to promote consistently safe work practices and proper operation of processes;

* Maintenance and inspection programs to ensure ongoing equipment reliability and integrity including equipment testing and inspection;

* A management of change process
